WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:08.360
So, we've been centered on 18.3 so far, and we're going to be talking about 19.0.

00:08.360 --> 00:14.060
Some of this stuff has been coming for a long time, and some of this stuff is fairly recent.

00:14.060 --> 00:18.820
So the first thing I'm going to call out is keep an eye out for version 6 of my intermediate

00:18.820 --> 00:20.800
React course.

00:20.800 --> 00:25.760
That should be the first time that I talk about React 19.

00:25.760 --> 00:30.040
I'm imagining that it's going to be out by that point, and if it's not, we'll probably

00:30.040 --> 00:35.520
push the date further so it can be out before I go teach it.

00:35.520 --> 00:39.920
But I just want to really emphasize that what you've learned today, I am confident in asserting

00:39.920 --> 00:45.480
that it will be still useful five years from now, because React doesn't change that quickly.

00:45.480 --> 00:49.320
The core model, which is what I taught you today, doesn't change very much.

00:49.320 --> 00:53.560
So there's no reason to wait to take courses or anything like that.

00:53.560 --> 00:56.520
It's all React at the end of the day.

00:56.520 --> 01:02.400
Most of the stuff that's in React V8 of this course still applies, right?

01:02.400 --> 01:06.960
Most of the modifications here were fairly minor.

01:06.960 --> 01:09.560
So it's about to be out.

01:09.560 --> 01:12.800
They've been talking about it for probably about a year now, and I'm going to say 95%

01:12.800 --> 01:17.560
of what I show you, I'm pretty confident in saying it's going to be unchanged, and there

01:17.560 --> 01:22.000
might be some corners around the edges of maybe some slight API changes or something

01:22.000 --> 01:24.160
like that, but I think the core concepts are going to be the same.

01:24.160 --> 01:28.440
It's in release candidate right now and has been for some time.

01:28.440 --> 01:33.880
So they don't anticipate that it's going to change very much.

01:33.880 --> 01:37.360
One of the things is use client and use server.

01:37.360 --> 01:41.240
You'll notice today I did not talk about these, and I did not want to, because I don't think

01:41.240 --> 01:46.880
it's useful for you today.

01:46.880 --> 01:51.880
React is now being bundled into more of a meta framework, so things like Next.js and

01:51.880 --> 01:56.360
Remix and all of those things, and one of the cool features that those things allow

01:56.360 --> 02:02.560
you is they allow you to say run this component on the server only or run this component on

02:02.560 --> 02:05.280
the browser only.

02:05.280 --> 02:10.280
We were just doing client-side React today, so that was nonsensical for us to talk about,

02:10.280 --> 02:12.600
but this is kind of cool for the future.

02:12.600 --> 02:17.360
Imagine that you can do things like run database queries directly from your React component.

02:17.360 --> 02:22.040
If you're using a server component, you can do that, and it's totally safe.

02:22.040 --> 02:29.400
By the same token, if you're writing Figma, a very client-heavy application, you don't

02:29.400 --> 02:30.880
want that stuff to run in the server.

02:30.880 --> 02:33.520
That doesn't make a lot of sense to render that stuff in the server.

02:33.520 --> 02:37.720
You're going to render that in the browser, so you'd use client on that.

02:37.920 --> 02:42.920
Just to give you an example of what that API looks like, if we go to, I don't know, header

02:42.920 --> 02:51.200
for some whatever reason, you can put up here at the top, use client, and this is now going

02:51.200 --> 02:54.680
to be guaranteed to only run in the client.

02:54.680 --> 02:56.320
I think it works per block as well.

02:56.320 --> 03:04.480
You could do, if we didn't have this, then you can do it here and so on.

03:04.480 --> 03:08.320
There's a bunch of different places you can use that are called directives.

03:08.320 --> 03:10.920
Same thing, you could say use server here.

03:10.920 --> 03:13.680
What's cool about use server in this particular case, it's just going to send down the complete

03:13.680 --> 03:14.680
markup.

03:14.680 --> 03:17.240
It's not going to send down the actual JavaScript to run it.

03:17.240 --> 03:20.400
It's just going to run everything in the server first and then send it down to the client,

03:20.400 --> 03:23.240
which is kind of cool.

03:23.240 --> 03:25.440
I think you can do it with effects and stuff like that.

03:25.440 --> 03:36.840
You can say use effect and use server in here, and then you have a server side effect that

03:36.840 --> 03:40.840
you can run there, which is also kind of interesting as well.

03:40.840 --> 03:46.640
Again, this only applies to meta frameworks like next, remix.

03:46.640 --> 03:50.760
You can build those meta frameworks yourself, but you have to get your hands pretty dirty

03:50.760 --> 03:52.440
with how React works.

03:52.960 --> 03:57.320
One of the things that I found interesting and useful, what happens if I have an API

03:57.320 --> 04:03.160
key that I'm using in a use server component?

04:03.160 --> 04:07.240
All it takes is one developer to go in there and say, oh, I actually need this to run on

04:07.240 --> 04:11.120
the client too and just delete the directive, and all of a sudden you're sending your secret

04:11.120 --> 04:13.760
keys down to your clients.

04:13.760 --> 04:18.320
You're one line away from a data breach, which is very scary.

04:18.320 --> 04:21.280
They have these things called taint unique value and taint object reference.

04:21.280 --> 04:26.120
It says, for these things that are running on the server, I don't care if something tells

04:26.120 --> 04:28.880
you to send this down, never send this down.

04:28.880 --> 04:32.920
That's what the taint unique value and taint object reference do, is they're just saying,

04:32.920 --> 04:37.040
I am putting extra guardrails on this that this will never leak.

04:37.040 --> 04:40.920
I thought that was a cool way of doing that.

04:40.920 --> 04:44.160
Cool.

04:44.160 --> 04:47.080
Any questions about that?

04:47.120 --> 04:51.880
You're just kind of adding a directive of where you want stuff to run, which I thought

04:51.880 --> 04:56.760
was a cool idea.

04:56.760 --> 05:01.440
Something else that, for the longest time we've had to use a thing called React Helmet.

05:01.440 --> 05:08.080
If you want to add stuff to, change the name of the document, here it says Padre Gino's.

05:08.080 --> 05:11.960
If you wanted to change that to order on the order page and contact on the contact page

05:11.960 --> 05:16.720
and stuff like that, you had to use something called React Helmet, which is a library from

05:16.720 --> 05:17.720
the NFL.

05:17.720 --> 05:21.600
It's a fun fact.

05:21.600 --> 05:24.000
You would render something into the helmet and then the helmet would put it in the head

05:24.000 --> 05:25.000
for you.

05:25.000 --> 05:26.680
That's how it would work.

05:26.680 --> 05:29.880
In React 19, they're just building that into React directly.

05:29.880 --> 05:33.480
If you render something like title here, it's just going to automatically put that in the

05:33.480 --> 05:34.480
head for you.

05:34.480 --> 05:35.480
You don't have to do anything special.

05:35.480 --> 05:36.480
It's just like, oh, title.

05:36.480 --> 05:38.480
That goes in the head.

05:38.480 --> 05:45.080
Same thing with links, so adding CSS documents or meta tags or anything like that.

05:45.080 --> 05:52.720
All that stuff that we used to use React Helmet for is all just built into React 19 now.

05:52.720 --> 05:59.080
We talked a little bit about preloading Preconnect earlier in the course.

05:59.080 --> 06:05.440
If you need a more interesting introduction to this, I found this article, which is pretty

06:05.440 --> 06:07.440
cool.

06:08.440 --> 06:15.560
They're called browser hints, and they allow you to say, hey, pre-do all the HTTPS handshakes.

06:15.560 --> 06:17.600
That's what Preconnect is for.

06:17.600 --> 06:22.000
I might need this here in a second, and I want you to go as fast as possible.

06:22.000 --> 06:26.280
Preconnect is like, do the handshake, get ready for the secure connection, but don't

06:26.280 --> 06:28.360
download anything.

06:28.360 --> 06:31.840
Then preload is like, no, go ahead and download this.

06:31.840 --> 06:33.160
It's done through browser hints.

06:33.920 --> 06:38.320
Built into the browser, it's not a particular React kind of thing.

06:38.320 --> 06:42.920
You would do something like this in React, and it's like, hey, I know this is about to

06:42.920 --> 06:46.400
open a text editor, because obviously this is the link, so I click here to open the text

06:46.400 --> 06:47.400
editor.

06:47.400 --> 06:52.120
You hear, it's like, get ahead of the user, download this first, so that when they click

06:52.120 --> 06:55.960
this link, we're immediately ready to go.

06:55.960 --> 06:59.920
Kind of cool, really interesting way of doing a hinting.

06:59.920 --> 07:02.080
The cool thing about this is browsers can ignore it.

07:02.080 --> 07:06.920
If it's in low battery mode or something like that, the browser will just ignore it.

07:06.920 --> 07:07.920
But it doesn't break it.

07:07.920 --> 07:09.520
They'll just have to wait longer.

07:09.520 --> 07:10.520
Web components.

07:10.520 --> 07:13.640
People have been clamoring for this for a long, long time.

